column12: Hydraulic Fluid Flow Management System and Method
column13: A hydraulic fluid flow management system and method includes three subsystems. The first subsystem is an engine mounted hydraulic fluid pump electrically operated flow control proportioning valve combination. The second subsystem is a hydraulic fluid flow distribution manifold assembly. The third subsystem is a computer operated controller and display which governs the operation of the electrically operated flow control proportioning valve combination.

column12: Improvements in or relating to Diving Apparatus.
column13: 7105. Day, J., and Day, G. March 18. Diving.-The shoulder joints F of metal casings for divers are of a cylindrical form, and the joints at the hips, knees, ankles, and elbows are of a ball-and-socket type, combined with cylindrical and knife-edge bearings J, J<1>, J<2>. The segmental bush J<1> is adjusted by means of a screw, and tops are provided for limiting the motion of the parts. Screwed caps K bearing against packing-rings protect the joints, and waterproof sleeves outside the joints may be filled in with a lubricant such as French chalk, lampblack, oil, tallow, soft soap, or the like. Instead of using a lubricant, the space within the sleeve may be filled with air at the same pressure as the water, so that air will pass through the joint in case of leakage, and will serve for breathing purposes. Air is supplied to the helmet A by a pipe G provided with a valve G<1> which is closed when the pressure of water exceeds that of the air, or by means of a lever G<2>, rod G<3>, and lever G<4>. The pipe H carries off the excess or vitiated air. Each arm casing carries a pair of jaws M for grasping objects under water. The jaws are pivoted to a hollow spindle, and are opened and closed by a nut and screwed spindles provided with a grooved collar at the end which engages with projections of the jaws. The helmet is provided with a pneumatic pad or cushion to reduce shocks. The joints may be used in connection with other forms of diving apparatus.

column12: Specifying SC and IT cut quartz resonators for optimal temperature compensated oscillator performance
column13: An oscillator includes dual resonators mounted in a helium filled coldweld holder. One resonator operates at anti-resonance into a load capacitance of about 20 picofarads, and operates on a third overtone frequency under noncontrolled temperature conditions. The other resonator operates on a fundamental mode at anti-resonance in a load capacitance of about 32 picofarads. Resonator crystals in a dual-crystal resonator may include a theta-angle shift to equalize frequency versus temperature curves at temperature extremes.

column12: Apparatus for recovering refrigerant from a cooling device
column13: The invention relates to an apparatus 1 for recovering refrigerant from a cooling device. Apparatus 1 has a housing 10 having a housing inlet 11 adapted to be connected to a cooling device and an housing outlet 12; a heat exchanger 15 in the housing having an heat exchange inlet 16 and a heat exchange outlet 17; a compressor 30 having an inlet 31 connected to the housing outlet, and an outlet 32 connected to the heat exchange inlet; a condenser 40 having a condenser inlet 42 connected to heat exchange outlet and a condenser outlet 43; and an apparatus outlet 50 to deliver liquid refrigerant to a storage device. In use, with the housing inlet connected to a cooling device, operation of the compressor draws refrigerant in liquid form from the cooling device into the housing where it is heated by the heat exchanger to convert it to a low pressure vapour, and the vapour is drawn into the compressor inlet where it is compressed and heated by the compressor into a hot high pressure vapour and expelled through the compressor outlet into the heat exchange inlet to heat the heat exchanger, and the vapour from the heat exchanger is passed through the condenser inlet where it is liquefied, and liquefied refrigerant from the condenser outlet can be passed to a refrigerant storage device.

column12: Apparatus for reclaiming refrigerant
column13: An apparatus for reclaiming contaminated refrigerant comprises a container 20 having an inlet 21 for receiving contaminated refrigerant, and a container outlet 22; a heater 30 for heating contaminated refrigerant in the container; at least one evaporator 40A,40B to convert liquid refrigerant into a vapour and to separate vapour refrigerant from contaminants, the or each evaporator having an liquid refrigerant inlet 41A,41B connected to the container outlet, and a vapour refrigerant evaporator outlet 42A,42B; at least one mechanical separator 60A,60B to separate vapour refrigerant from contaminants, the or each separator being connected to the evaporator outlet, and providing a separator outlet 62A,62B; and a heat exchanger 70 having an inlet 71 connected to the separator outlet, said heat exchanger adapted to convert vapour refrigerant into liquid refrigerant, and said heat exchanger having an outlet 72 for connection to a refrigerant storage device 80. In use contaminated refrigerant is passed through the container, evaporator, and separator to remove contaminants. Preferably a drain is associated with each element of the apparatus.

column12: Kitchen worktop safety barrier
column13: A safety barrier 1 is supported from the front edge of a kitchen worktop 2. The barrier 1 may be secured to the work surface by barrier supports (4, figure 2) which are affixed to the work top 2 and into which the barrier 1 is inserted. A barrier (1 figure 9) may also be secured to the front panel (3, figure 9) of a drawer in the unit immediately below the worktop (2, figure 9). The barrier 1 is intended to prevent access to the work top 2 and/or cooker hot plates. The barrier 1 may also shield pots, pans, kettles or food from the view of children and also prevent individuals from reaching such objects. The barrier 1 may be used to protect selected areas of the worktop 2, the complete worktop, and 'built in' or 'free standing' cooker tops.

Parameterized recursive network architecture with topological addressing
column13: A digital data communications network that supports efficient, scalable routing of data and use of network resources by combining a recursive division of the network into hierarchical sub-networks with repeating parameterized general purpose link communication protocols and an addressing methodology that reflects the physical structure of the underlying network hardware. The sub-division of the network enhances security by reducing the amount of the network visible to an attack and by insulating the network hardware itself from attack. The fixed bandwidth range at each sub-network level allows quality of service to be assured and controlled. The routing of data is aided by a topological addressing scheme that allows data packets to be forwarded towards their destination based on only local knowledge of the network structure, with automatic support for mobility and multicasting. The repeating structures in the network greatly simplify network management and reduce the effort to engineer new network capabilities.

ELECTRICAL POWER CELL ENERGIZED BY HIGH FREQUENCY ELECTROMAGNETIC RADIATION
column13: A power cell for generating useful electrical power from high frequency electromagnetic radiation comprising a spiral-wound, multi-layer film forming a cylindrical body with a central opening (10) for receiving the radiation source (11). The film has in succession a conductive grounded emitter layer (E), a first intermediate layer (12) of dielectric material, a second intermediate layer (C') of a material having a substantial Compton effect, a conductive collector layer (C), a third intermediate layer (13) of the same dielectric material, a conductive retarding layer (R), and an insulating layer (14). The collector and emitter layers are to be connected to the opposite terminals of a load. A bleeder regulator (15) is connected between the retarding and collector layers to pass excess charge on the retarding layer to the collector layer.

Displacement of the arm 4 causes the ends of the pin 14 to ride up on the side of the grooves and displace the spindle axially with respect to the body and so disengage portions 8, 15. The arm can then rotate freely and is returned manually to the indexed position. Specification 803,995 is referred to.

column12: PRODUCING CALCIUM CYANIDE AT A MINE SITE USING EASILY TRANSPORTABLE STARTING MATERIALS.
column13: The present invention is a method by which the mine can obtain a supply of calcium cyanide for use in its leaching operations. Specifically, one preferred method within the scope of the invention involves producing hydrogen cyanide directly at a mine site using formamide as a starting material. Alternative methods of producing hydrogen cyanide at the mine site using easily transportable starting materials, such as methanol and urea, are disclosed. The hydrogen cyanide is neutralized at the mine site with slaked lime (Ca(OH)<sub>2 </sub>)to form the calcium cyanide.

column12: Separation and collection of analyte materials
column13: A cyclone separator, for the separation of particulate materials from a particle-bearing gas or vapor, in which the particle-bearing gas or vapor is injected into a separating chamber ( 10 ), and the particles centrifuged to a separating chamber wall ( 12 ) of the separating chamber ( 10 ) for collection, the separating chamber wall ( 12 ) being wetted by a liquid to assist in collection of the centrifuged particles from the separating chamber wall ( 12 ), the separating chamber wall ( 12 ) being at least partly porous, the separating chamber wall ( 12 ) being wetted by the passage of the liquid through the porous part, to provide a more uniform wetting of the separating chamber wall ( 12 ), and hence more efficient particulate collection than previously achieved by prior art methods. The cyclone separator of the invention may also be used for the separation and collection of gas or vapor-born vapors, in place of particulates. An instrument for the separation, collection and detection and/or analysis of gas or vapor-born materials using a cyclone separator in accordance with the invention is described.

column12: Bias modulation active linearization for broadband amplifiers
column13: A power amplifier circuit for broadband data communication over a path in a communication network can reduce or avoid gain compression, provide low distortion amplification performance, and can accommodate a wider input signal amplitude range. A dynamic variable bias current circuit can be coupled to a differential pair of transistors to provide a dynamic variable bias current thereto as a function of input signal amplitude. Bias current is increased when input signal amplitude exceeds a threshold voltage established by an offset or level-shifting circuit. The frequency response of the bias current circuit can track the full frequency content of the input signal, rather than its envelope. Gain degeneration can be modulated in concert with the bias current modulation to stabilize amplifier gain.

column13: 994,457. Reciprocating pumps. DESMO Ltd. June 27, 1961 [June 28, 1960], No. 22542/60. Heading F1A. The movable part 20, Fig. 18, is raised from the inoperative position shown in Fig. 16 by supplying oil under pressure to a cylinder 69 from the pump 61 and pipe 68, the pump being operated by a solenoid 59 energized cyclically by a "flasher unit" 58 through a time delay switch 83 from the vehicle battery 60, the switch maintaining its contacts closed for a predetermined time after manual operation. As shown in Fig. 17, the solenoid 59 operates a plunger 62 against the urge of a spring 73 to move the piston 63 of the pump 61 in a bore 64. Fluid is supplied to the bore from a reservoir 65 and pipe 66 and leaves the bore 64 through a non-return outlet valve 67 and passes through the pipe 68 to the cylinder 69. The solenoid is energized repeatedly during a period sufficient to produce a working pressure of 30 1b./sq. inch which is sufficient to maintain the mirror raised against spring action. When the switch 83 opens the mirror is retained in the raised position by the maintaining of the pressure in the pipe 68 and cylinder 69 because of the non-return valve 67. However on energizing the solenoid again the pressure is increased to about 50 1bs./sq. inch which is sufficient to open a relief valve 75 against the action of a spring 77, adjustable by a screw cap 78. When the valve 75 is opened the fluid pressure acts on an annular flange 80 which is of such an area that the valve will remain open even when the pressure falls below the 30 1bs./sq. inch necessary to maintain the mirror raised and when this occurs the mirror is returned to its inoperative position by a spring (not shown). The pump may be pneumatically operated.

POSITION PARAMETERIZED RECURSIVE NETWORK ARCHITECTURE WITH TOPOLOGICAL ADDRESSING
column13: A digital data communications network that supports efficient, scalable routing of data and use of network resources by combining a recursive division of the network into hierarchical sub-networks with repeating parameterized general purpose link communication protocols and an addressing methodology that reflects the physical structure of the underlying network hardware. The sub-division of the network enhances security by reducing the amount of the network visible to an attack and by insulating the network hardware itself from attack. The fixed bandwidth range at each sub-network level allows quality of service to be assured and controlled. The routing of data is aided by a topological addressing scheme that allows data packets to be forwarded towards their destination based on only local knowledge of the network structure, with automatic support for mobility and multicasting. The repeating structures in the network greatly simplify network management and reduce the effort to engineer new network capabilities.

column13: Concentrated aqueous alkaline isotropic liquid detergent composition comprising a mixture of nonionic and anionic surfactants and dissolved hydrogen peroxide. The composition is suitable for use as a laundry detergent and since it is substantially free from ethanol or other C1-4 monohydric alcohols, stability of the composition is increased and the danger of explosion from a mixture of low flashpoint alcohol and peroxide is reduced.

column13: A power amplifier circuit for broadband data communication over a path in a communication network can reduce or avoid gain compression, provide low distortion amplification performance, and can accommodate a wider input signal amplitude range. A dynamic variable bias current circuit can be coupled to a differential pair of transistors to provide a dynamic variable bias current thereto as a function of input signal amplitude. Bias current is increased when input signal amplitude exceeds a threshold voltage established by an offset or level-shifting circuit. The frequency response of the bias current circuit can track the full frequency content of the input signal, rather than its envelope. Gain degeneration can be modulated in concert with the bias current modulation to stabilize amplifier gain.

column13: A kit for repairing breaks in laminated glass comprising a vacuum plate adapted to be positioned over a break in a surface of laminated glass. The vacuum plate includes suction cups for securing the plate to the glass surface. An injector assembly is included for connection to the vacuum plate adjacent the suction cups and adapted to form a seal with the glass surface surrounding the break. An adjustment screw is provided for connection to the vacuum plate adjacent the suction cups and opposite the injector assembly for pivoting the vacuum plate about the suction cups to adjust the angle of contact of the injector assembly with the glass surface for different curvatures of surface so as to maintain the seal. Repair fluid is provided and is adapted to be introduced into the injector assembly, and a pump is provided for connection to the injector assembly in order to apply negative and positive pressure to the break and thereby fill the break with the repair fluid.

column13: 931,399. Laminates. GEORGE SPENCER, MOULTON & CO. Ltd. June 3, 1960 [March 3, 1959], No. 7368/59. Class 140. [Also in Group XXVI] A rubberized cord fabric diaphragm for a vacuum brake cylinder comprises two or more plies which consist of a very fine weft serving merely to hold the strong warp cords in position during rubberizing of the fabric, are cut on the bias, and are superimposed upon one another with an intervening layer of rubber and the directions of the strong warp cords in the different plies intersecting. The diaphragm may be made by assembling the plies to form a band, joining the ends of the band, and shaping to the required form on a cone former. These operations may be followed by curing in a mould or in a steam heater while wrapped on a former.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS USEFUL FOR REDUCING NEUROMUSCULOSKELETAL IMBALANCE
column13: There is provided a method of alleviating or reducing the symptoms of uneven pelvic rotation in a patient suffering therefrom; comprising: (a) selecting the patient; (b) identifying the patient's functionally short leg; (c) positioni ng the patient in a substantially prone position, thereby reducing any weight supported by the patient's pelvis; (d) while the patient is in the substantially prone position, simultaneously elevating a front portion of the patient's cephalic thigh adjacent the forwardly rotated acetabular joint and removing restrictions to the rearward rotation of said acetabular joint, while elevating a cephalic portion of the front region of the ilium o n the other side; and, (e) repeating step (d) at least once per month. Therapeutic wedges usef ul in the method are also provided. There is also provided a method of relieving or alleviating the symptoms of chronic spinal movement in the neck in a patient suffering therefrom, comprising: (a) selecting the patient; (b) identifying the direction of spin al movement/misalignment in the patient's neck; (c) positioning the patient in a substantially horizontal position looking upward so as to reduce any weight supported by the patient's neck; and, (d) applying a consistent force to the back of t he patient's neck in the region of the second to fourth cervical vertebrae, thereby urgin g lateral displacement of the cervical spine in a direction opposite to the direction of spinal movement/misalignment in the patient's neck. Therapeutic forms such as neck rolls useful in the method are also provided.

column13: 25,647. Day, B. J. Nov. 21. Gearing.-Apparatus for dipping articles into liquids for cleansing or pickling purposes prior to tinning and like processes consists of two unequal cranks c, d, Fig. 4, connected to a single suspending-rope and operated alternately, according as a long or short dipping-stroke is required, by shafts f driven by a motor h through worm gearing and controlled by clutches k connected by links l. In another device, shown in Fig. 5, a single crank p is mounted on a disc n secured to a shaft m, the crank being connected by worm and bevel gearing q, u driven from an independent shaft by a pinion z and controlled by a clutch x. For a short stroke, the clutch is disconnected so that the disc n and crank are driven directly by the shaft m. For a long stroke, the shaft m is disconnected and the crank driven from the pinion z and gearing u, q. In a modification, shown in Fig. 7, the crank p is driven, for the long stroke, through spur gearing 2, 3, 1 controlled by a clutch 4, the lever of which has two stops which alternately engage a weighted lever mounted on the spindle 5 to throw the clutch de6nitely into or out of action. In a second modification, shown in Fig. 10, the crank is driven by epicyclic gearing 13, 12 and worm gearing 11, the wheel 13 being loose on the shaft m and provided with a brake 15, and the disc n keyed to the shaft. For a short stroke, the brake is released so that the wheel 13 and disc n are locked together by the worm gearing ; by applying the brake, the wheel 12 rolls on the wheel 13 and the crank turns on its centre O. The gears may be proportioned so that the crank is always vertical.

column12: BIAS MODULATION ACTIVE LINEARIZATION FOR BROADBAND AMPLIFIERS
column13: A power amplifier circuit for broadband data communication over a path in a communication network can reduce or avoid gain compression, provide low distortion amplification performance, and can accommodate a wider input signal amplitude range. A dynamic variable bias current circuit can be coupled to a common emitter bias node of a differential pair of transistors to provide a dynamic variable bias current thereto as a function of an input signal amplitude of an input signal. Bias current is increased when input signal amplitude exceeds a threshold voltage established by an offset or level-shifting circuit. The frequency response of the bias current circuit can track the frequency content of the input signal. A delay in the signal path to the differential pair can phase-align the bias current to the amplification by the differential pair. A dynamic variable supply voltage can be based on an envelope of the input signal.

Position parameterized recursive network architecture with topological addressing
column13: A digital data communications network that supports efficient, scalable routing of data and use of network resources by combining a recursive division of the network into hierarchical sub-networks with repeating parameterized general purpose link communication protocols and an addressing methodology that reflects the physical structure of the underlying network hardware. The sub-division of the network enhances security by reducing the amount of the network visible to an attack and by insulating the network hardware itself from attack. The fixed bandwidth range at each sub-network level allows quality of service to be assured and controlled. The routing of data is aided by a topological addressing scheme that allows data packets to be forwarded towards their destination based on only local knowledge of the network structure, with automatic support for mobility and multicasting. The repeating structures in the network greatly simplify network management and reduce the effort to engineer new network capabilities.

column12: ELECTRIC POWER CELL ENERGIZED BY PARTICLE AND ELECTROMAGNETIC RADIATION
column13: A power cell (30) which converts ionizing radiation (14) into electrical energy. The power cell includes a multi-layer composite source element (60) which includes a charged particle emitter layer (63), first and second source dielectric layers (62), a source collector layer (61) and a source retarding layer (65). The source element is disposed within a multi-layer composite shield element (70) having an absorber (73), first and second shield dielectric layers (72), a shield collector layer (71), and a shield retarding layer (75). An anode (A) is connected to the emitter layer (63) and a cathode (C) to the collector layer (61). The emitter layer (63) produces charged particles which interact with the dielectric layers (12 and 64) to eject electrons which are collected by the collector layer (61) to generate a potential between the anode (A) and the cathode (C).

A central buffing and draw gear comprises a shell member 12 attached to a forward follower 13 and telescopically movable over a shell 10 forming a hydraulic fluid reservoir welded to a rear follower 2, a casing member 1 welded to the follower 2 and fixed to an intermediate follower 3 having an annular projection 5, springs 6, 14, and a spindle 15 which may co-operate with a separate piston 7 movable in hydraulic fluid in the casing 1. When a load is applied through a yoke to the follower 13, assembly shear pins 16 are broken, and the spring 14 is alone compressed until the follower 13 abuts the end of the spindle 15, whereafter the springs 6, 14 and the hydraulic unit operate in parallel. column13:
There is provided a method of alleviating or reducing the symptoms of uneven pelvic rotation in a patient suffering therefrom, comprising: (a) selecting the patient; (b) identifying the patient's functionally short leg; (c) positioning the patient in a substantially prone position, thereby reducing any weight supported by the patient's pelvis; (d) while the patient is in the substantially prone position, simultaneously elevating a front portion of the patient's cephalic thigh adjacent the forwardly rotated acetabular joint and removing restrictions to the rearward rotation of said acetabular joint, while elevating a cephalic portion of the front region of the ilium on the other side; and, (e) repeating step (d) at least once per month. Therapeutic wedges useful in the method are also provided. 

   There is also provided a method of relieving or alleviating the symptoms of chronic spinal movement in the neck in a patient suffering therefrom, comprising: (a) selecting the patient; (b) identifying the direction of spinal movement/misalignment in the patient's neck; (c) positioning the patient in a substantially horizontal position looking upward so as to reduce any weight supported by the patient's neck; and, (d) applying a consistent force to the back of the patient's neck in the region of the second to fourth cervical vertebrae, thereby urging lateral displacement of the cervical spine in a direction opposite to the direction of spinal movement/misalignment in the patient's neck. Therapeutic forms such as neck rolls useful in the method are also provided.

column13: A power amplifier circuit for broadband data communication over a path in a communication network can reduce or avoid gain compression, provide low distortion amplification performance, and can accommodate a wider input signal amplitude range. A dynamic variable bias current circuit can be coupled to a common emitter bias node of a differential pair of transistors to provide a dynamic variable bias current thereto as a function of an input signal amplitude of an input signal. Bias current is increased when input signal amplitude exceeds a threshold voltage established by an offset or level-shifting circuit. The frequency response of the bias current circuit can track the frequency content of the input signal. A delay in the signal path to the differential pair can phase-align the bias current to the amplification by the differential pair. A dynamic variable supply voltage can be based on an envelope of the input signal.

column13: A power amplifier circuit for broadband data communication over a path in a communication network can reduce or avoid gain compression, provide low distortion amplification performance, and can accommodate a wider input signal amplitude range. A dynamic variable bias current circuit can be coupled to a common emitter bias node of a differential pair of transistors to provide a dynamic variable bias current thereto as a function of an input signal amplitude of an input signal. Bias current is increased when input signal amplitude exceeds a threshold voltage established by an offset or level-shifting circuit. The frequency response of the bias current circuit can track the frequency content of the input signal. A delay in the signal path to the differential pair can phase-align the bias current to the amplification by the differential pair. A dynamic variable supply voltage can be based on an envelope of the input signal.

column12: PARAMETERIZED RECURSIVE NETWORK ARCHITECTURE WITH TOPOLOGICAL ADDRESSING
column13: A digital data communications network that supports efficient, scalable routing of data and use of network resources by combining a recursive division of the network into hierarchical sub-networks with repeating parameterized general purpose link communication protocols and an addressing methodology that reflects the physical structure of the underlying network hardware. The sub-division of the network enhances security by reducing the amount of the network visible to an attack and by insulating the network hardware itself from attack. The fixed bandwidth range at each sub-network level allows quality of service to be assured and controlled. The routing of data is aided by a topological addressing scheme that allows data packets to be forwarded towards their destination based on only local knowledge of the network structure, with automatic support for mobility and multicasting. The repeating structures in the network greatly simplify network management and reduce the effort to engineer new network capabilities

column12: PRODUCING CALCIUM CYANIDE AT A MINE SITE USING EASILY TRANSPORTABLE STARTING MATERIALS
column13: The present invention is a method by which the mine can obtain a supply of calcium cyanide for use in its leaching operations. Specifically, one preferred method within the scope of the invention involves producing hydrogen cyanide directly at a mine site using formamide as a starting material. Alternative methods of producing hydrogen cyanide at the mine site using easily transportable starting materials, such as methanol and urea, are disclosed. The hydrogen cyanide is neutralized at the mine site with slaked lime (Ca(OH)2 )to form the calcium cyanide.

column12: Chain-saw mortise cutting apparatus
column13: An apparatus for forming the joint components of mortice and tenon joints using a chain-saw comprises two guide parts to one of which the guide bar of the chain saw is adapted to be secured and the other of which is adapted to be secured to the timber length to be formed with the mortise and tenon joint part. The apparatus may incorporate means for varying the position of the mortice to be cut both as regards position with respect to the longitudinal edges of the timber length and angularly with respect thereto. The invention enables joint parts to be formed, in the field, in timber lengths, with a considerable precision, thereby avoiding the costly need to transport such timber lengths to the work-shop for treatment employing expensive specialist equipment. The invention is of application in the formation of joint parts in timber lengths used in the construction of fencing and, also, in the formation of mortice and tenon joints in timbers employed in the construction of timber framed buildings.

column13: A waste discharge monitor and monitoring system especially for a ship, boat or other seagoing vessel, monitors and may prevent the discharge of waste or sewerage. The monitor is triggered by opening of a valve. The waste discharge monitor comprises a valve with a sensor operatively coupled to a recorder, a power supply and a tamper resistant means. The sensor detects opening/closing of the valve and a signal is transmitted wirelessly to the recorder to generate a log when the valve is opened/closed. The device may be battery operated and the data logging recorder may be a solid state memory device such as read only memory (ROM or EPROM). The device stores both universal time and GPS coordinates of the vessel when an incident occurs. Opening of the valve may be prevented in prohibited locations. An automatic identification system assesses the number, proximity and identity or type of other vessels and so the system may override opening of the valve in certain circumstances.

METHODS AND COMPOSITIONS RELATED TO EMULSIFIED GASSING AGENTS FOR SENSITIZING EXPLOSIVE COMPOSITIONS
column13: Methods and compositions for providing an emulsified gassing agent for use in sensitizing emulsion explosive compositions. The emulsified gassing agent is preferably a water-in-oil emulsion such that it is easily combinable with water-in-oil explosive emulsion compositions. The emulsified gassing agent and the emulsion explosive can be kept separate until the point in time immediately prior to introduction into the blasting site. The emulsified gassing agent will contain a gassing agent which releases gas when placed in contact with the emulsion explosive composition. One preferred gassing agent is sodium nitrite, but other gassing agents are also usable. The emulsion may also comprise a companion salt such as calcium or sodium nitrate, a vehicle such as No. 2 diesel oil, a surfactant, and a carrier such as water.

The container may have a lock 30, a rigid outer wall made from opaque material, a hinged or removable lid and an audible safety alarm. There may be means for enabling the removal of articles from the container in the form of a bar with a foot, the container may be portable and have a series of chambers. The container may be connected to a second container by a frame device having a carrying handle. Each article stored in the container may have a separate retaining cover in the form of a wire in a grid pattern which may be used in conjunction with encircling straps or a hinged lid.

column12: Electrical power cell energized by high frequency electromagnetic radiation
column13: A power cell for generating useful electrical power from high frequency electromagnetic radiation comprising a spiral-wound, multi-layer film forming a cylindrical body with a central opening for receiving the radiation source. The film has in succession a conductive grounded emitter layer, a first intermediate layer of dielectric material, a second intermediate layer of a material having a substantial Compton effect, a conductive collector layer, a third intermediate layer of the same dielectric material, a conductive retarding layer, and an insulating layer. The collector and emitter layers are to be connected to the opposite terminals of a load. A bleeder regulator is connected between the retarding and collector layers to pass excess charge on the retarding layer to the collector layer.

Snubbed railroad car truck
column13: A truck for a railroad car includes two spaced side frames which resiliently support ends of a transversely positioned bolster in a window formed in each side frame. On each side of the bolster is a vertical recess formed having opposing convex-shaped sides which engage with end walls of vertical ribs formed on the inner and outer side of spaced sidewalls of the side frame window. In downwardly projecting pedestal jaws formed at each end of each side frame and having selectively spaced sidewalls are journaled axle ends of a front and a rear wheelset. Interposed between each axle end and a roof of the pedestal jaw is a bearing adapter having a convex top surface to engage with a concave surface of the roof of the side frame pedestal jaw. During travel of the truck, a relative rolling movement between the wheelsets, side frames and bolster may occur because of the interaction of the convex sides of the bolster recess with the ribs of the side frame, and because of a like interaction between the convex top surface of the adapter with the roof of the pedestal jaw.

Methods of blasting using nitrogen-free explosives
column13: A method of blasting using non-nitrogen containing explosives which protect the environment from pollution of nitrogen compounds is provided. The method includes the following steps: (1) combining an oxidizer, a fuel, water, and a binder such that an explosive is formed which is substantially free of nitrogen; (2) placing the explosive in a location selected for blasting; and (3) initiating said explosive. The nitrogen-free oxidizer may be a perchlorate such as sodium perchlorate. Using this method, the explosive may be a water gel, emulsion, a dry explosive, or a liquid oxygen explosive.

column12: Position parameterized recursive network architecture with topological addressing
column13: A digital data communications network that supports efficient, scalable routing of data and use of network resources by combining a recursive division of the network into hierarchical sub-networks with repeating parameterized general purpose link communication protocols and an addressing methodology that reflects the physical structure of the underlying network hardware. The sub-division of the network enhances security by reducing the amount of the network visible to an attack and by insulating the network hardware itself from attack. The fixed bandwidth range at each sub-network level allows quality of service to be assured and controlled. The routing of data is aided by a topological addressing scheme that allows data packets to be forwarded towards their destination based on only local knowledge of the network structure, with automatic support for mobility and multicasting. The repeating structures in the network greatly simplify network management and reduce the effort to engineer new network capabilities.

column12: PROCESS OF MAKING MICROPOROUS SHEETS
AIRBORNE PARTICLE COLLECTION ARRANGEMENTS AND METHODS
column13: An aircraft (1) has a porous collection plate (12) mounted exposed to the airflow. A supply (17) of fluid is connected to the rear surface (14) of the plate (12) so that fluid flows through the plate and forms a film (30) on its forward, exposed surface (13). Particles (31) in the airflow impinge the exposed surface (13) of the plate (12) and become trapped in the fluid film (30). A gutter (20) at the lower edge of the plate (12) collects fluid and particles as they flow down the plate. The gutter (20) connects with a collector (22) in which the particles and fluid are collected. The collector (22) may include a concentrator so that excess fluid can be returned via a conduit (60) to the fluid supply. Particles in the collector (22) are either stored for later analysis or can be analyzed on board by an analyzer (50).

column12: Producing Calcium Cyanide At A Mine Site Using Easily Transportable Starting Materials
column13: The present invention is a method by which the mine can obtain a supply of calcium cyanide for use in its leaching operations. Specifically, one preferred method within the scope of the invention involves producing hydrogen cyanide directly at a mine site using formamide as a starting material. Alternative methods of producing hydrogen cyanide at the mine site using easily transportable starting materials, such as methanol and urea, are disclosed. The hydrogen cyanide is neutralized at the mine site with slaked lime (Ca(OH) 2 ) to form the calcium cyanide.

column13: A cyclone separator, for the separation of particulate materials from a particle-bearing gas or vapour, in which the particle-bearing gas or vapour is injected into a separating chamber (10), and the particles centrifuged to a separating chamber wall (12) of the separating chamber (10) for collection, the separating chamber wall (12) being wetted by a liquid to assist in collection of the centrifuged particles from the separating chamber wall (12), the separating chamber wall (12) being at least partly porous, the separating chamber wall (12) being wetted by the passage of the liquid through the porous part, to provide a more uniform wetting of the separating chamber wall (12), and hence more efficient particulate collection than previously achieved by prior art methods. column12: Electric power cell energized by particle and electromagnetic radiation
column13: A power cell which converts ionizing radiation into electrical energy. The power cell includes a multi-layer composite source element which includes a charged particle emitter layer, first and second source dielectric layers, a source collector layer and a source retarding layer. The source element is disposed within a multi-layer composite shield element having an absorber layer, first and second shield dielectric layers, a shield collector layer, and a shield retarding layer. An anode is connected to the emitter layer and a cathode to the collector layer. The emitter layer produces charged particles which interact with the dielectric layers to eject electrons which are collected by the collector layer to generate a potential between the anode and the cathode.

column12: LENS SYSTEMS
column13: 1,269,133. Lens systems. RANK ORGANISATION Ltd. July 14, 1970 [July 16, 1969], No. 35797/69. Heading G2J. An optical objective comprises a "Cooke triplet formation" I, II, III and a divergent component IV axially spaced behind the rear surface of the triplet by 0‹25-0‹75F where F is the equivalent focal length of the complete objective, all the components being made of light-transmitting synthetic resins, and the triplet including an aspheric surface. The term "Cooke triplet formation" refers to a substantially anastigmatic Cooke triplet which is in itself fully corrected apart from a large Petzval sum, or to an assembly of three components having the appearance of a Cooke triplet, but which in itself is not substantially anastigmatic, the presence of the divergent component being necessary for reduction in the Petzval sum and also for completing correction of other aberations. The aspheric surface is preferably the front surface of the third component. When the divergent component is spaced at least 0À2F from the image plane, the triplet is modified so that the four components are corrected in conjunction. When the divergent component is less than 0À2F from the image plane, the triplet is selfcorrecting. The two outer components of the triplet and the divergent component may be of polymethyl methacrylate, and the centre component of the triplet of polystyrene. Optical data are given for three examples. The objective preferably has an external stop in front of the Cooke triplet, and two such objectives may be arranged to share a common diaphragm to form a copying or relay lens.

column12: POSITION PARAMETERIZED RECURSIVE NETWORK ARCHITECTURE WITH TOPOLOGICAL ADDRESSING
column13: A digital data communications network that supports efficient, scalable routing of data and use of network resources by combining a recursive division of the network into hierarchical sub-networks with repeating parameterized general purpose link communication protocols and an addressing methodology that reflects the physical structure of the underlying network hardware. The sub-division of the network enhances security by reducing the amount of the network visible to an attack and by insulating the network hardware itself from attack. The fixed bandwidth range at each sub-network level allows quality of service to be assured and controlled. The routing of data is aided by a topological addressing scheme that allows data packets to be forwarded towards their destination based on only local knowledge of the network structure, with automatic support for mobility and multicasting. The repeating structures in the network greatly simplify network management and reduce the effort to engineer new network capabilities.

column12: ENTDECKUNGS- UND DIAGNOSEVERFAHREN MIT 5- METHYLCYTOSIN-DNA-GLYCOSYLASE
column13: The present invention provides methods for identification of methylated, and/or potentially methylatable CpG dinucleotides in genomic DNA sequences, and methods for isolating genomic DNA sequences comprising methylated CpG dinucleotide sequences. The present invention further provides methods for comparison of the methylation status of specific CpG dinucleotides, and patterns thereof between normal and diseased genomic DNA sequences, along with methods for determining all potentially methylatable CpG dinucleotides in a genomic DNA sample. Specifically, the present invention discloses a novel use of 5-methylcytosine DNA glycosylase (5-MCDG) in combination with art-recognized DNA base excision repair (BER) enzymes, and in particular embodiments, in combination with DNA methyltransferase to specifically label methylated CpG dinucleotide sequences in genomic DNA sequences.

column13: A remote procedure call handler generated by a third party is hosted by a server, wherein the remote procedure call handler is configured to receive, from an end user device, a remote procedure call relating to a document associated with by a third party application. A remote procedure call relating to the document is received from a first user device, via interframe communication. The document is updated by the remote procedure call handler, based on the remote procedure call. An event notification message informing a second end user device of the update to the document is transmitted to a second user device, via interframe communication.

column12: Improved Method of and Means for Producing Designs or Surfaces for Enamelling and other Purposes
column13: 16,486. Greenley, C. J., and Day, J. Aug. 16. Lithographic and like printing. - Pictures, designs, or lettering in colours are transferred from one stone or plate to another, or to enamelled metal, poctery, glass, tiles, or other articles on transparent sheets coated with gelatine. These are made by cleaning glass plates with French chalk, spreading warm gelatine on them, and pressing sheets of cellulcid,mica, or like material thereon ; the gelatine and celluloid &c. are afterwards stripped off together. In transferring designs for enamelling, the colours used are gronped as shades of red, yellow, and blue; all the prints in one group are successively transferred, and dusted with their proper shades, before a firing operation, black and the darker shades being transferred first. There are thus not more than three firing operations for any number of colours. The gelatine sheets may be cleaned with turpentine or benzoline.

column12: Improvements in or relating to clothes-horses

Class 52(5) A clothes-horse comprises upright frames varying- in width from top to bottom and horizontal rails pivotally secured to the frames at points of differing widths so that each set of rails and the associated frames fold and unfold with a parallelogram action about vertical axes and clothes hanging on an upper rail of the erected horse do not rest on those on a lower rail. As shown, a clothes-horse has three frames 10, 11, 12, formed by metal tube or bar elements 13, 14, 15 and rails 20, 21, 22 pivotally secured to the frames by hollow spigots 24, apertured plates 23, and pegs 28. The clothes-horse may consist of one or of more than two sections.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR REAL-TIME DETECTION OF ANOMALIES IN DATABASE USAGE
column13: A system and method for real-time detection of anomalies in database or application usage is disclosed. Embodiments provide a mechanism to detect anomalies in database or application usage, such as data exfiltration attempts, first by identifying correlations (e.g., patterns of normalcy) in events across different heterogeneous data streams (such as those associated with ordinary, authorized and benign database usage, workstation usage, user behavior or application usage) and second by identifying deviations/anomalies from these patterns of normalcy across data streams in real-time as data is being accessed. An alert is issued upon detection of an anomaly, wherein a type of alert is determined based on a characteristic of the detected anomaly.

Process for making filter tow
column13: A crimped filament tow, suitable for use in making cigarette filter rods, is made by a process in which porous particles, such as activated carbon particles, are adhered to the filaments by an adhesive. Deactivation of the adsorbent surfaces of the particles by the adhesive is limited by loading the particles with a material, such as water, which can generate a gaseous emission, such as steam, from the particles so as to open up access to the adsorbent interior surfaces of the particles. The filaments, which may be cellulose acetate, may have a cross-section having concave portions, such as are provided by multi-lobal cross-sections, in which the adhered particles may lie to protect them against shedding by abrasion of the filaments against machine surfaces. The particles and the adhesive may be applied to the banded tow (3) at the same time, in the form of a dispersion of the particles in the adhesive, and may be applied directly before the crimping step. The crimped tow may then be heated to generate the gaseous emission from the particles as well as drying and curing the adhesive. The product tow can be processed on standard equipment to make efficient filter rods from which cigarette filter tips can be made which give significantly increased and selective retention of key smoke constituents.

Process for Making Filter Tow
column13: A crimped filament tow, suitable for use in making cigarette filter rods, is made by a process in which porous particles, such as activated carbon particles, are adhered to the filaments by an adhesive. Deactivation of the adsorbent surfaces of the particles by the adhesive is limited by loading the particles with a material, such as water, which can generate a gaseous emission, such as steam, from the particles so as to open up access to the adsorbent interior surfaces of the particles. The filaments, which may be cellulose acetate, may have a cross-section having concave portions, such as are provided by multi-lobal cross-sections, in which the adhered particles may lie to protect them against shedding by abrasion of the filaments against machine surfaces. The particles and the adhesive may be applied to the banded tow at the same time, in the form of a dispersion of the particles in the adhesive, and may be applied directly before the crimping step. The crimped tow may then be heated to generate the gaseous emission from the particles as well as drying and curing the adhesive. The product tow can be processed on standard equipment to make efficient filter rods from which cigarette filter tips can be made which give significantly increased and selective retention of key smoke constituents.

column12: Implantable cardiac cardioverter/defibrillator with EMI suppression filter with independent ground connection
column13: An implantable defibrillator, which may include cardioversion and pacemaker capabilities, which has EMI filters which are not susceptible to defibrillation shocks and which reduce or eliminate the effects of charging noise on sensing circuits used for continuous confirmation. A first filter capacitor is provided between a sense electrode, which may include pacing capabilities, and a ground reference within a hermetically sealed can containing a pulse/shock generator. A second filter capacitor is provided between a sensing/pacing reference electrode, which may also be a high voltage or shock electrode, and the ground reference. In addition, there is a third filter capacitor between the ground reference and the can. Preferably, the connections of the first, second and third filter capacitors are physically as well as electrically adjacent to each other. The filter capacitors are housed in the can and in or adjacent to a feedthrough assembly which passes through the can. Most preferably, the filter capacitors are discoidal capacitors mounted in or adjacent to the feedthrough.

GRAYSCALE HISTOGRAM GENERATION
column13: In a graphics processing unit (GPU), receiving an input image comprising an array of pixels. Each pixel having a grayscale value from a range of N grayscale values. For each particular input patch of pixels of a set of input patches partitioning the input image and in parallel for each particular grayscale value the range, counting the number of pixels in the particular input patch having the particular grayscale value. In parallel for each particular input patch of pixels of a set of input patches partitioning the input image, creating an output image patch as an ordered sequence of N pixels, with the color value of the nth pixel in each corresponding output patch representing the count of pixels in the particular input patch having the nth grayscale value. Combining the output image patches into a single composite output image of N pixels, the pixel value of the nth pixel in the single composite output image corresponding to the count of pixels in the input image having the nth grayscale value.

Application of 4-[1-oxoalkyl]-2,5-oxazolidinediones in selective stereospecific formation of biologically active alpha -lactams
column13: The present invention relates to a method for producing novel 4-[1-oxoalkyl]-2,5-oxazolidinediones, (4-1 OOD), and their use in a stereoselective method of producing beta-lactam-containing compounds which include several biologically active compounds such as the well-known families of penicillin and cephalosporin antibiotics. The method of the present invention involves generally the reaction of the above-described 4-[1-oxoalkyl]-2,5-oxazolidinediones so produced with a thiol amine having a geometry amenable to forming the precursor of the desired beta-lactam-containing compound or, in one scheme, forming the beta-lactam-containing compound itself directly. This is done either by direct reaction of the 4-1 OOD with a thiol amine (which by one pathway proceeds directly to the beta-lactam-containing compound) or by first converting the 4-1 OOD to its 2-[1-oxoalkyl]-2-amino acid form before its reaction with the thiol amine; and then forming the beta lactam by action of cyanogen). The beta-lactam-containing compounds can be further modified according to methods known in the art to produce specific derivatives as desired.

column12: FLOW CONTROL METHOD AND MEANS
column13: The invention provides a method of controlling gas flow in an axial flow compressor (C) in which the flow at least at one chosen station in the direction of flow through the compressor the flow is sensed at a series of circumferentially spaced positions. Flow variations above a predetermined limit are evaluated to give an actuating response if a disturbance above a predetermined acceptable level is detected. When such a disturbance is detected, higher pressure gas bled from further downstream is injected at said station to supplement the main gas flow there. An incipient rotating stall cell will appear as a variation occurring sequentially at the circumferentially spaced positions. By responding to such a condition with a pressure injection flow, it is found possible to suppress both rotating stall and surge conditions in the compressor before the disturbance develops fully. The same means can be arranged to counter steady state distortion.

column12: Method and system for managing network communications
column13: A system that incorporates teachings of the present disclosure may include, for example avoiding data copy and task switching by processing protocol headers of network PDUs as a serial tape to be processed in order such as by a single method. Other processing includes reducing stages and simplifying protocol processing and multiplexing during network communications. Address changing in an active network can be implemented by assigning multiple addresses to an entity so that a new address can replace the old address. Peer-to-peer application searching can be performed among networks that can be accessible or non-accessible networks. Utilizing anycast sets that include selected and alternative addresses to enable immediate or near immediate alternative route selection on failure or congestion. Other embodiments are disclosed.

column12: ADJUSTABLE TRACHEOSTOMA VALVE AND HEAT AND MOISTURE EXCHANGER
column13: To provide an improved adjustable tracheostoma valve which enables the valve to close automatically when a sufficient air pressure passes through the valve and causes the valve to close and redirect the exhaled air through the voice prosthesis in order to allow the user to produce voice.SOLUTION: A flexible membrane 24 supports a closure member 22 in a natural state and also when air is being exhaled through a tracheostoma valve 10. When air is being exhaled through the tracheostoma valve 10, the force of the air passing by the closure member 22 tends to cause the closure member 22 to move toward a second opening 20. When the force of air being exhaled is strong enough, the closure member 22 can be pressed fully against the second opening 20, to redirect the exhaled air through the user's voice prosthesis to allow the user to produce voice.SELECTED DRAWING: Figure 4

column12: ELECTRICAL WIRE AND CABLE
column13: An electrical wire or cable has electrical insulation or a jacket which comprises a cross-linked blend of: (a) an aromatic polymer that has a char residue of at least 25 % at 850°C and contains one or more aliphatic moieties; and (b) a polymer having a char residue of not more than 15 % at 850°C; the blend containing at least 20 % by weight of the aromatic polymer based on the total weight of the polymer but having an overall molar carbon to hydrogen ratio of not more than 1.15. The wire insulation exhibits reduced erosion compared with the uncross-linked insulation when subjected to a tracking test, and exhibits a disproportionately reduced char residue, compared with the char residue of the components, which leads to a high degree of electrical tracking resistance.

column12: USER PROGRAMMABLE LIGHTING CONTROLLER SYSTEM AND METHOD
column13: Lighting systems wherein the lighting effects can be customized by the user to include different colors or different color changing effects. The lighting systems are arranged to be used with different emitters, including but not limited to solid state emitters such as light emitting diodes (LEDs), wherein the LEDs can be divided into zones. The lighting produced in each of those zones can be customized to be a unique color of light or to change colors in a particular way. The lighting system also allows for the different zones to be programmed to cooperate, such as allowing for particular colors of light to flow from one zone to another. Other lighting characteristics can also be controlled, including but not limited to color intensity, speed of color changing or the different colors included in the sequence of color changing.

column12: Adjustable tracheostoma valve and heat and moisture exchanger
column13: An adjustable tracheostoma valve includes a housing having a first opening that is adapted to open to a tracheostoma and a second opening that opens to ambient. The housing includes a lower housing portion defining the first opening and an upper housing portion movably attached to the lower housing portion and defining the second opening. A closure member is disposed in the housing and adapted to close the second opening. A flexible membrane includes a first region connected to the closure member and a plurality of spiral shaped legs extending from the first region and connected to the housing. The upper and lower housings are axially adjustable relative to one another to adjust an amount of air flow through the valve that would cause closure of the closure member. A heat and moisture exchanger is disposed in the housing between the first opening and the second opening.

column12: Ladder standoff device
column13: A standoff device for positioning a ladder with respect to a supporting structure which is temporarily and rigidly attached to the upper end of a ladder for the purpose of holding the ladder away from the structure against which the ladder is leaning to provide more stability and means to provide a comfortable distance between the user and the structure during tasks such as painting, power washing house frame and sidings, and for the installation and cleaning of gutters, for carpentry, roofing, tree trimming and pruning. The standoff comprises a pivotal frame which is moveably and adjustably secured to a selected rung of the ladder with the pivotal movement limited by chain, rope, strap, strut, telescoping member, or other holding means attached to a lower portion of the ladder such as a lower rung. The standoff device includes a frame having extendable legs having padded rollers journal led on the end thereof which contact the structure. Moreover, an additional pair of rollers extend inwardly from the legs forma a “V-shaped” support means for leaning against vertical support structures such as columns or trees. The frame includes other rollers journal led inwardly at selected obtuse angles so that the frame is configured for use against the outside or inside corner of a structure, a pole or a tree.

column12: ADJUSTABLE TRACHEOSTOMA VALVE AND HEAT AND MOISTURE EXCHANGER
column13: The present invention relates to an adjustable tracheostoma valve capable of being adjusted to a level comfortable to a patient. According to the present invention, the adjustable tracheostoma valve comprises a housing having a first opening configured to be opened to a tracheostoma and a second opening opened to the circumference thereof. The housing comprises a lower housing portion defining the first opening and an upper housing portion movably attached to the lower housing portion and defining the second opening. A closing member is disposed in the housing and is suitable for closing the second opening. A flexible membrane comprises a first area connected to the closing member and a plurality of spiral legs extended from the first area and connected to the housing. The upper and lower housing portions can be adjusted with each other in an axial direction to adjust the amount of an air flow through the valve, which causes closure of the closing member. A heat and moisture exchanger is disposed between the first opening and the second opening in the housing.

column12: Compressor head
column13: A compressor head 10 comprises reciprocating and chamber-head members 20 and 30 defining a compression chamber 60. The surfaces of the reciprocating member and the chamber-head member form a complimentary relationship so that as the reciprocating member approaches the chamber-head member they have a progressively increasing surface contact, at least one of the two members has a flexible surface portion for forming the progressive contact. The compressor head may comprise a back support member (240). Preferably said contact progresses from the periphery inwards. The flexible surface portion may be a diaphragm 26, 36. The chamber-head assembly may have a self adjusting mechanism including biassing spring 34 and cushioning arrangement 80 which adjust the chamber-head's position automatically in response to changes in outlet pressure. The reciprocating member may include a fluid cushioning arrangement. In another embodiment the reciprocating member (120) may comprise a core (121) and a sleeve (127) forming a slide bearing inside cylinder (142) with a diaphragm (136) fitted between the core and the sleeve.

column12: Transparent infrared radiation absorption system
column13: Apparatus for minimizing the transmission of long wave infrared energy without significantly affecting the transmission of solar energy to provide an energy efficient building component is disclosed. A flexible plastic substrate is used having a thickness of no more than approximately 20 mils. A long wave infrared radiation absorbing material is fixed to the plastic substrate. The substrate and the absorber in combination are at least 94% transmissive to visible solar radiation so that transmission of solar energy is substantially unaffected. However, the substrate and the absorber absorb sufficient long wave infrared radiation so that transmission of at least 80% of all incident long wave radiation is prevented, in large measure blocking the transmission of heat energy through the system.

APPARATUS AND A METHOD OF DETERMINING THE PRESENCE OF AN ALUMINA LAYER ON A SURFACE OF A COMPONENT
column13: Provided is a method for determining the presence of an alumina layer on a surface of a component. The method includes illuminating a surface of a component with radiation; detecting radiation emitted at a particular wavelength; analyzing the detected radiation; to determine the thickness of the alumina at at least one point on the surface of the component; and comparing the determined thickness of the alumina at the at least one point on the surface of the component with a predetermined thickness of alumina at that point to decide if the thickness of alumina at the at least one point on the surface of the component is satisfactory.

column12: Recovery of platinum group metals from scrap and residues.
column13:
This invention relates to the recovery of platinum group metals and gold and silver from scrap and residues and also to the separation of silver from the other precious metals referred to. In more detail the process for the recovery of platinum group metals, silver and gold from precious metal containing residue comprises the following steps:
 (a) smelting the said precious metal containing residue with leach residue and a flux to produce
 (i) a slag containing FeO, CaO and SiO 2  and (ii) copper matte phase containing Ni,Fe,S, and the platinum group metals, Au, Ag, Se and Te. (b) removing, if necessary, any excess of the elements Iron or nickel or compounds thereof from the matte phase produced by step (a) by oxidation thus converting the said elements or compounds thereof to their respective oxides which then report to the slag phase, (c) contacting the matte phase produced by step (a) or the said matte phase after oxidation step (b) with one or more metals selected from the group Cu, Ni and Fe so as to produce a separate immiscible me- taiiic phase containing platinum group metals, silver and gold, (d) optionally recirculating the said separate metallic phase produced by step (c) to contact a separately produced matte phase produced by a step (a) or by steps (a) and (b) so as to at least partially redistribute the silver present out of the metallic phase, and, (e) recovering silver from the matte phase and the platinum group metals, gold and the proportion of silver which remains from the metallic phase.

column12: RECOVERY OF PLATINUM GROUP METALS FROM SCRAP AND RESIDUES
Recovery of platinum group metals from scrap and residues
column13: A process for the recovery of platinum group metals, Ag and Au from a precious metal containing residue which includes the platinum group metals, Ag and Au together with Fe, Cu, Ni, Se and Te, the process comprising the following steps: (a) smelting the precious metal containing residue with leach residue including S and a flux to product (i) a slag and (ii) a copper matte phase containing S, the platinum group metals, Au, Ag, Se and Te, and an excess of Ni and/or Fe as defined in step (b) below, (b) removing excess of the elements Fe or Ni or compounds thereof from the matte phase produced by step (a) by oxidation thus converting the elements or compounds thereof to their respective oxides which then report to the slag phase, the excess being defined as more than about 10% by weight of iron, more than about 15% by weight of nickel or more than about 20% by weight of the total of iron and nickel, based on the weight of the matte phase, (c) contacting the matte phase produced after oxidation step (b) in liquid form with one or more molten metals selected from the group consisting of Cu, Ni and Fe so as to produce a separate immiscible metallic phase containing platinum group metals, silver and gold, and (d) recovering silver from the matte phase and the platinum group metals, gold and the proportion of silver which remains from the metallic phase.

column12: A rotor arrangement for a gas turbine
column13: With highly loaded rotors and stators problems can occur with secondary flows sweeping low momentum fluid across the blades reducing efficiency. By provision of collector slots 35 to collect the secondary air and direct that air to a return slot 37 in a rotor hub 32 it is possible to provide impetus to the collected secondary flow C to an outlet slot 36 such that there is dispersal of the secondary flow C and therefore reduce the effects upon the overall performance of a gas turbine engine incorporating the arrangement.

column13: L'invention décrit un procédé de régulation d'écoulement de gaz dans un compresseur centrifuge axial, selon lequel l'écoulement, à au moins un poste donné dans le sens d'écoulement à travers le compresseur, est détecté en une série de positions espacées de manière circonférentielle. Des fluctuations d'écoulement au-dessus d'une limite prédéterminée sont évaluées afin de produire une réaction d'actionnement si une perturbation se situant au-dessus d'un niveau acceptable prédéterminé est détectée. Lorsqu'une perturbation est détectée, un gaz à plus haute pression soutiré d'un endroit plus loin en aval est injecté dans ledit poste pour y compléter l'écoulement de gaz principal. Une cellule de décrochage tournant naissante va apparaître sous forme d'une fluctuation ayant lieu séquentiellement à des positions espacées de manière circonférentielle. Lorsqu'on réagit à une telle condition par un écoulement à injection sous pression, il devient possible de supprimer des conditions de décrochage tournant et de pompage dans le compresseur avant que la perturbation ne se développe entièrement. Les mêmes moyens peuvent être agencés pour contrecarrer la distortion en régime permanent.

column12: ELECTRICAL WIRE
column13: An electrical wire comprises an elongate electrical conductor and electrical insulation that comprises: a) an inner insulating layer which comprises polyamide or polyester having aliphatic moieties; and b) an outer insulating layer which comprises an aromatic polymer. The wire exhibits good electrical and mechanical properties associated with highly aromatic polymers together with high resistance to electrical arcing.

column12: ADJUSTABLE TRACHEOSTOMA VALVE AND HEAT AND MOISTURE EXCHANGER
column13: An adjustable tracheostoma valve includes a housing having a first opening that is adapted to open to a tracheostoma and a second opening that opens to ambient. The housing includes a lower housing portion defining the first opening and an upper housing portion movably attached to the lower housing portion and defining the second opening. A closure member is disposed in the housing and adapted to close the second opening. A flexible membrane includes a first region connected to the closure member and a plurality of spiral shaped legs extending from the first region and connected to the housing. The upper and lower housings are axially adjustable relative to one another to adjust an amount of air flow through the valve that would cause closure of the closure member. A heat and moisture exchanger is disposed in the housing between the first opening and the second opening.

column12: APPLICATION OF 4-[1-OXOALKYL]-2,5-OXAZOLIDINEDIONES IN SELECTIVE STEREOSPECIFIC FORMATION OF BIOLOGICALLY ACTIVE BETA-LACTAMS
column13: The present invention relates to a method for producing novel 4-[1-oxoalkyl]-2,5-oxazolidinediones, (4-1 OOD), and their use in a stereoselective method of producing beta-lactam-containing compounds which include several biologically active compounds such as the well-known families of penicillin and cephalosporin antibiotics. The method of the present invention involves generally the reaction of the above-described 4-[1-oxoalkyl]-2,5-oxazolidinediones so produced with a thiol amine having a geometry amenable to forming the precursor of the desired beta-lactam-containing compound or, in one scheme, forming the beta-lactam-containing compound itself directly. This is done either by direct reaction of the 4-1 OOD with a thiol amine (which by one pathway proceeds directly to the beta-lactam-containing compound) or by first converting the 4-1 OOD to its 2-[1-oxoalkyl]-2-amino acid form before its reaction with the thiol amine; and then forming the beta lactam by action of cyanogen. The beta-lactam-containing compounds can be further modified according to methods known in the art to produce specific derivatives as desired.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR MANAGING NETWORK COMMUNICATIONS
column13: A system that incorporates teachings of the present disclosure may include, for example avoiding data copy and task switching by processing protocol headers of network PDUs as a serial tape to be processed in order such as by a single method. Other processing includes reducing stages and simplifying protocol processing and multiplexing during network communications. Address changing in an active network can be implemented by assigning multiple addresses to an entity so that a new address can replace the old address. Peer-to-peer application searching can be performed among networks that can be accessible or non-accessible networks. Utilizing anycast sets that include selected and alternative addresses to enable immediate or near immediate alternative route selection on failure or congestion. Other embodiments are disclosed.

column12: FABRY-PEROT OPTICAL FILTERS
column13: Simple polarisation independent wavelength tuning components (filters) employ a filter element, such as a Fabry-Perot etalon element, which is such that light input thereto undergoes two element transitions with orthogonal polarisation states before being output, in order to suppress polarisation noise. In one arrangement, two etalon filters 20, 21, are separated by a half wave plate 22 providing the necessary polarisation rotation. The two etalon filters and the half wave plate comprise a single element rotatable about the single axis. 23 and 26 are optical fibres. column12: HYDRAULICALLY-ACTUATED FAIL-SAFE STROKE-LIMITING PISTON
column13: An apparatus for limiting the travel of a slave piston (110) in a slave piston cylinder (100) in a compression release engine brake is disclosed. The apparatus provides stroke-limiting means and independent lash adjustment means which may be installed in a common rail, variable valve actuation system. The independent lash adjustment means comprises a sleeve (300) around the slave piston (110), threadably mounted in the brake housing (40). The stroke-limiting means comprises a slave piston (110) in a slave piston cylinder (100), a trigger valve (90) and a hydraulic circuit connected thereto. The slave piston stroke is limited when a lower flow port (130) in the slave piston cylinder (100) is opened to drain (81) slightly before high-pressure flow is cut off through an upper flow port (120) in the slave piston cylinder (100).

GRAYSCALE HISTOGRAM GENERATION
column13: In a graphics processing unit (GPU), receiving an input image comprising an array of pixels. Each pixel having a grayscale value from a range of N grayscale values. For each particular input patch of pixels of a set of input patches partitioning the input image and in parallel for each particular grayscale value the range, counting the number of pixels in the particular input patch having the particular grayscale value. In parallel for each particular input patch of pixels of a set of input patches partitioning the input image, creating an output image patch as an ordered sequence of N pixels, with the color value of the n th pixel in each corresponding output patch representing the count of pixels in the particular input patch having the n th grayscale value. Combining the output image patches into a single composite output image of N pixels, the pixel value of the n th pixel in the single composite output image corresponding to the count of pixels in the input image having the n th grayscale value.

column12: HEAT-SEALABLE MARKING ELEMENTS AND METHODS FOR LABELLING ARTICLES FORMED OF TEXTILE OR LIKE MATERIALS
column13: 1,201,713. Transfers. POLYMARK Ltd. 23 Jan., 1969 [2 Feb., 1968], No. 5539/68. Heading B6C. A heat transfer comprises an inked design on a layer of a heat curing film-forming resin system in the presence of blocked cross-linking groups and under acid conditions, said resin being heat-curable to form an inert, insoluble and wear-resistant marking on said surface. The film-forming resin system used in the present invention comprises (1) a film-forming heat-sealable resin bearing functional groups, such as hydroxyl, amino, amido or carboxyl groups, (2) cross-linking groups which are blocked by substitution such as methoxymethyl or ethoxy-methyl groups such groups containing a substituted methylol group and (3) if the resin itself does not have acidic properties, curing agents are present which are organic acids or acid-yielding substances which acids or substances are inactive at normal room temperatures but become effective to promote curing of the resin at the higher temperatures used for heat-sealing the marking element to a surface to be marked. Transfers of this kind are applied under heat and pressure to the surface to be marked with the continuous layer of the resin system in immediate contact with the surface to be marked. The continuous layer becomes permanently bonded to the article and, due to the release properties of the temporary support the latter may then be removed leaving the transfer in place.

RECOVERY OF PLATINUM GROUP METALS FROM SCRAP AND RESIDUES
column13: This invention relates to the recovery of platinum group metals and gold and silver from scrap and residues and also to the separation of silver from the other precious metals referred to. In more detail the process for the recovery of platinum group metals, silver and gold from precious metal containing residue comprises the following steps: (a) smelting the said precious metal containing residue with leach residue and a flux to produce (i) a slag containing FeO, CaO and SiO2 and (ii) a copper matte phase containing Ni,Fe,S, and the platinum group metals, Au, Ag, Se and Te. (b) removing, if necessary, any excess of the elements iron or nickel or compounds thereof from the matte phase produced by step (a) by oxidation thus converting the said elements or compounds thereof to their respective oxides which then report to the slag phase, (c) contacting the matte phase produced by step (a) or the said matte phase after oxidation step (b) with one or more metals selected from the group Cu, Ni and Fe so as to produce a separate immiscible metallic phase containing platinum group metals, silver and gold, (d) optionally recirculating the said separate metallic phase produced by step (c) to contact a separately produced matte phase produced by a step (a) or by steps (a) and (b) so as to at least partially redistribute the silver present out of the metallic phase, and, (e) recovering silver from the matte phase and the platinum group metals, gold and the proportion of silver which remains from the metallic phase.

column12: APPLICATION OF 4- 1-OXOALKYL]-2,5-OXAZOLIDINEDIONES IN SELECTIVE STEREOSPECIFIC FORMATION OF BIOLOGICALLY ACTIVE BETA-LACTAMS.
column13: Procédé de production de nouveaux 4-[1-oxoalkyl]-2,5-oxazolidinediones, (4-1 OOD), et leur utilisation dans un procédé stéréosélectif de production de composés contenant de la bêta-lactame qui comprennent plusieurs composés biologiquement actifs tels que les familles d'antibiotiques bien connus, à savoir la pénicilline et la céphalosporine. Le procédé ci-décrit comprend généralement la réaction des 4-[1-oxalkyl]-2,5-oxazolidinediones ainsi produits avec une thiolamine possédant une géometrie que l'on peut modifier pour former le précurseur du composé désiré contenant la bêta-lactame ou, dans une variante, pour former directement le composé contenant la bêta-lactame. On parvient à ce résultat soit par la réaction directe du 4-1 OOD avec une thiolamine (ce qui donne directement un composé contenant la bêta-lactame, soit en convertissant d'abord le 4-1 OOD dans sa forme 2-[1-oxoalkyl]-2-aminoacide avant sa réaction avec la thiolamine, et en formant ensuite la bêta-lactame par l'action du cyanogène. Les composés contenant la bêta-lactame peuvent être modifiés par la suite selon les procédés connus pour produire les dérivés spécifiques désirés.
