column12: Certificate validation system
column13: A certificate validation mechanism is provided for a network interface. The certificate validation mechanism maintains a certificate cache containing local copies of certificates with associated validity indications. The certificate validation mechanism is operable to compare a certificate associated with a received message to the certificate cache and, where the certificate associated with the received message is held in the certificate cache, to associate with the message an indication of validity retrieved from the certificate cache. By providing a cache for certificates local to the network interface, the need always to verify a certificate by reference to a public repository is removed. If a certificate is not held in the local cache, then it can still be necessary to query the public repository. Nevertheless, the verification mechanism provides more immediate verification of certificate validity as this can be made locally without the cost and time of the remote verification at the public repository. The verification mechanism can form part of portal for a network interface.

column12: Polymeric compositions
column13: A composition comprises a thermoplastic polymer and a mineral filler characterized in that, either the mineral filler is coated with an uncured epoxy resin and the polymer contains an amine hardener therefor, or the filler is coated with the amine hardener and the polymer contains the epoxy resin, or the filler is coated with both the epoxy resin and the amine hardener and incorporated in the polymer before the epoxy resin has completely cured. The filler may also be treated with an ethylenically unsaturated silane. Suitable fillers include glass fibres, mica and asbestos. Suitable polymers include polyoxymethylenes, polyvinyl chloride, vinyl chloride-vinyl acetate-maleic acid copolymer and nylon.ALSO:Glass and asbestos fibres are treated with one or more of the components of an epoxy resin before a thermoplastic polymer is applied thereto. In particular, when the fibres are treated with an uncured epoxy resin and the thermoplastic polymer contains an amine hardener therefor, or the fibres are treated with the amine hardener and the thermoplastic polymer contains uncured epoxy resin, or the fibres are treated with both epoxy resin and amine hardener and the thermoplastic polymer is applied before the epoxy resin has completely cured. The fibres may also be treated with an ethylenically unsaturated silane. Suitable thermoplastic polymers include polyoxymethylenes, polyvinyl chloride, vinyl chloride-vinyl acetate-maleic acid copolymer and Nylon.

column13: The invention discloses a topical antipenetrant formulation of niclosamide. The preferred formulation contains about one percent by weight niclosamide, 40 to 55 percent by weight of propylene glycol and about 20 to 30 percent by weight of 95% ethanol, 20 to 25% by weight polyethylene glycol 400 and from about 0.1 to 10% by weight water. column12: A combustion chamber
column13: A three-stage lean burn combustion chamber (28) comprises a primary combustion zone (36), a secondary combustion zone (40) and a tertiary combustion zone (44). Each of the combustion zones (36,40,44) is supplied with premixed fuel and air by respective fuel and air mixing ducts (54,70,92). The fuel and air mixing ducts (54,70,92) have a plurality of air injections apertures (62,64,76,98) spaced apart in the direction of flow through the fuel and air mixing ducts (54,70,92). The apertures (62,64,76,98) reduce the magnitude of the fluctuations in the fuel to air ratio of the fuel and air mixture supplied into the at least one combustion zone (36,40,44). This reduces the generation of harmful vibrations in the combustion chamber (28).

column13: 14,348. Day, J., Timewell, A., and Timewell, C. E. June 29. Axle-caps; lubricating.-A lubricating axle-cap for the wheels of vehicles is shown in the position for receiving lubricant in Fig. 1, and closed in Fig. 3. The sliding cap B, secured within the ordinary cap A by the two rims C, H, has two keys G, and the rim H has two corresponding slots. After the lubricant has been passed through the aperture F into the cap, the keys are brought opposite the slots, and the sliding cap is pushed inwards against the action of the spring L. The sliding cap is then secured by rotating it, whereby the keys also grip against the inner surface of the cap A, which is made slightly elliptical. The washer E prevents leakage.

column12: Method for producing and shipping metal cyanide salts
column13: Metal cyanide suitable for shipment is prepared by introducing an aqueous metal cyanide feed stream to a crystallizer to form a slurry of metal cyanide crystals in their mother liquor. The crystallization step occurs at a temperature between 30.degree. C. and 70.degree. C., and preferably between 50.degree. C. to about 60.degree. C. The metal cyanide crystals are separated from their mother liquor to form a wet cake product containing from about 75 to 98 wt. % anhydrous metal cyanide crystals, from about 4 to 24 wt. % water, and from about 1 to 5 wt. % of metal hydroxide. The wet cake product is placed into a shipping container for shipment to a desired location. A metal cyanide solution is prepared by dissolving the wet cake product.

column12: In-line testing of the concentration of a chemical in a water-containing system
column13: In-line testing of the concentration of a selected chemical in water by measuring the amount of light at a predetermined wavelength transmitted through the water. The detected signal is transmitted to a pre-calibrated measuring and display means which calculates the concentration of the chemical and by reference to predetermined concentration thresholds provides a visual display of acceptable or non-acceptable additive concentration. The apparatus may be fitted to the pipe work of a central heating system for measuring inhibitor concentration. The apparatus may comprise casing 1, test button 2, 'on' indicator 3 and a display of LED indicators 4, 5, 6. The operative pushes test button 2 causing power to flow to two UV light emitters (8, 9 Fig. 2). The light is received at photocell (11, Fig.2). The apparatus may be used in the initial commissioning or ongoing monitoring of a water-containing system.

column12: REINFORCED THERMOPLASTIC RESIN MATERIALS
column13: 1,268,755. Extruding composite materials. NATIONAL RESEARCH DEVELOPMENT CORP. 10 June, 1969 [13 June, 1968], No. 28120/68. Heading B5A. [Also in Division C3] Granules or pellets of carbon fibre reinforced thermoplastic resin are made by passing the fibres and resin through the barrel of a screw extruder, wherein the constituents are mixed while the barrel is at a temperature in the region of or in excess of the softening temperature of the resin, and chopping or breaking the solidified extrudate. The pellets are particularly intended as starting material for processes such as injection, compression or extrusion moulding. Preferably the extruder screw tapers in the direction of extrusion and co-operates with stationary screw blades fixed to the barrel. The carbon fibres may be fed to the extruder as short lengths or continuous tows. In examples, 10 parts by weight of carbon fibre are mixed with 90 parts by weight of each of polystyrene, nylon 6,6, polymethyl methacrylate and poly- 4-methyl-pentene-1; 12 parts by weight with 88 parts by weight acrylonitrile-butadiene-styrene and 5 parts by weight with 95 parts by weight of an ethylene/vinyl acetate copolymer.

column12: TOPISCH ANZUWENDENDE NICLOSAMID ENTHALTENDE LOTION
column13: The invention discloses a topical antipenetrant formulation of niclosamide. The preferred formulation contains about one percent by weight niclosamide, 40 to 55 percent by weight of propylene glycol and about 20 to 30 percent by weight of 95% ethanol, 20 to 25% by weight polyethylene glycol 400 and from about 0.1 to 10% by weight water. This formulation provides an effective barrier on the skin, preventing the penetration of Schistosoma cercariae, the infective stage of the parasite life cycle.

column12: PAINT
column13: A top coat paint for protecting a surface from external rust-staining comprises a film-forming binder and a solid substance having a water solubility of at least 0.1 gram per litre and capable of reacting with rust. The substance capable of reacting with rust is capable of chelating iron and has a high formation constant for complexation with Fe(III). The chelate complex formed with Fe(III) is substantially colourless and no less water-soluble than the said substance. The said substance is (a) a salt of a substituted aliphatic organic acid or of a 1,3-diketone, or (b) an aliphatic hydroxamic acid of formula (I), where R is an alkyl group of 1 to 18 carbon atoms, or a salt thereof. It may be produced by mixing the ingredients.
